value.value: The process of coupling tryptophan to tryptophanyl-tRNA in a mitochondrion, catalyzed by tryptophanyl-tRNA synthetase. In tRNA aminoacylation, the amino acid is first activated by linkage to AMP and then transferred to either the 2'- or the 3'-hydroxyl group of the 3'-adenosine residue of the tRNA.

The process of coupling tyrosine to tyrosyl-tRNA in a mitochondrion, catalyzed by tyrosyl-tRNA synthetase. In tRNA aminoacylation, the amino acid is first activated by linkage to AMP and then transferred to either the 2'- or the 3'-hydroxyl group of the 3'-adenosine residue of the tRNA.

The process of coupling valine to valyl-tRNA in a mitochondrion, catalyzed by valyl-tRNA synthetase. In tRNA aminoacylation, the amino acid is first activated by linkage to AMP and then transferred to either the 2'- or the 3'-hydroxyl group of the 3'-adenosine residue of the tRNA.

The action characteristic of growth hormone, a peptide hormone that is secreted by the anterior pituitary or the placenta into the circulation, and binds to membrane receptors in target tissues to stimulate body growth.

A nuclear telomere cap complex that is formed by the association of telomeric ssDNA- and dsDNA-binding proteins with telomeric DNA, and is involved in telomere protection and recruitment of telomerase. The complex is known to contain TERF1, TERF2, POT1, RAP1, TINF2 and ACD in mammalian cells, and Pot1, Tpz1, Rap1, Rif1, Rif2 and Taz1 in Saccharomyces. Taz1 and Rap1 (or their mammalian equivalents) form a dsDNA-binding subcomplex, Pot1 and Tpz1 form an ssDNA-binding subcomplex, and the two subcomplexes are bridged by Poz1, which acts as an effector molecule along with Ccq1.
The chemical reactions and pathways involving kynurenine, the amino acid 3-(2-aminobenzoyl)-alanine.

label.value: chromosome organization involved in meiotic cell cycle

value.value: A process of chromosome organization that is involved in a meiotic cell cycle.

A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a synaptonemal complex. A synaptonemal complex is a proteinaceous scaffold formed between homologous chromosomes during meiosis.
The controlled breakdown of a synaptonemal complex.
A receptor complex that consists of two identical subunits and binds growth hormone.

label.value: eukaryotic translation initiation factor 3 complex assembly

value.value: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form the eukaryotic translation initiation factor 3 complex.

label.value: meiotic attachment of telomere to nuclear envelope

value.value: The meiotic cell cycle process in which physical connections are formed between telomeric heterochromatin and the nuclear envelope, facilitating bouquet formation.

label.value: protein localization to chromosome, telomeric region

value.value: Any process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained at, the telomeric region of a chromosome.

label.value: establishment of protein localization to chromosome

value.value: The directed movement of a protein to a specific location on a chromosome.

label.value: establishment of protein localization to telomere

value.value: The directed movement of a protein to a specific location in the telomeric region of a chromosome.

label.value: regulation of establishment of protein localization

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of a protein to a specific location.

label.value: regulation of establishment of protein localization to chromosome

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of a protein to a specific location on a chromosome.

label.value: regulation of establishment of protein localization to telomere

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of a protein to a specific location in the telomeric region of a chromosome.
Catalysis of the reaction: 2-oxoglutarate + H+ + isochorismate = 5-enolpyruvoyl-6-hydroxy-2-succinyl-cyclohex-3-ene-1-carboxylate + CO2.
Catalysis of the reaction: 5-enolpyruvoyl-6-hydroxy-2-succinyl-cyclohex-3-ene-1-carboxylate = (1R,6R)-2-succinyl-6-hydroxycyclohexa-2,4-diene-1-carboxylate + pyruvate.
The formation of a protein trimer, a macromolecular structure consisting of three noncovalently associated identical or nonidentical subunits.
The formation of a protein homotrimer, a macromolecular structure consisting of three noncovalently associated identical subunits.
The formation of a protein heterotrimer, a macromolecular structure consisting of three noncovalently associated subunits, of which not all are identical.

A protein complex that contains a histone deacetylase and is part of the chromatin remodeling machinery. In Saccharomyces cerevisiae this complex contains the Rpd3p, Sin3p, Ume1p, Pho23p, Sap30p, Sds3p, Cti6p, Rxt2p, Rxt3p, Dep1p, Ume6p, Ash1p, Dot6p, Snt1, Sif2p, Set3p, Hos2p, Tos4p and Tod6p proteins.
A histone deacetylase complex that is part of the chromatin remodeling machinery. In Saccharomyces cerevisiae this complex contains Snt2p, Ecm5p and Rpd3p.
The transfer of multiple ADP-ribose residues from NAD to a protein amino acid, forming a poly(ADP-ribose) chain.
The ADP-ribosylation by a protein of one or more of its own amino acid residues, or residues on an identical protein.

A protein complex that contains the protein-tyrosine kinase CSK and the GTPase-activating protein (GAP)-associated p62 (GAP-A.p62); may mediate translocation of proteins, including GAP and CSK, to membrane or cytoskeletal regions upon c-Src activation.

definition.value: Note that the gene/protein name 'APC' should not be confused with the abbreviation for 'anaphase promoting complex'.

value.value: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a transcription factor TFIIIB complex.
A sulfur oxidation process that proceeds via the reaction catalyzed by sulfur dioxygenase, and requires the presence of oxygen.
A sulfide oxidation process that proceeds via the reaction catalyzed by sulfide:quinone oxidoreductase.
A sulfide oxidation process that proceeds via the reaction catalyzed by sulfide dehydrogenase.
A sulfide oxidation process that proceeds via the reaction catalyzed by sulfur dioxygenase.
Catalysis of the reaction: H2S (hydrogen sulfide) + a quinone = S0 (sulfane sulfur) + a hydroquinone.

definition.value: Note that EC:1.8.5.4 describes this reaction as bacterial-specific, but it has also been observed in eukaryotes (PMID:22852582, PMID:10224084).

value.value: Catalysis of the reaction: hydrogen sulfide + oxidized cytochrome c = S + reduced cytochrome c.
Catalysis of the reaction: a perthiol + 4 Fe3+ + 3 H2O = sulfite + a thiol + 4 Fe2+ + 8 H+.
Any apoptotic process in a lymphocyte, a leukocyte commonly found in the blood and lymph that has the characteristics of a large nucleus, a neutral staining cytoplasm, and prominent heterochromatin.

definition.value: Note that a lymphocyte is a cell of the B cell, T cell, or natural killer cell lineage (CL:0000542).

value.value: Any process that modulates the occurrence or rate of lymphocyte death by apoptotic process.

definition.value: Note that a lymphocyte is a cell of the B cell, T cell, or natural killer cell lineage (CL:0000542).

label.value: negative regulation of lymphocyte apoptotic process

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of lymphocyte death by apoptotic process.

definition.value: Note that a lymphocyte is a cell of the B cell, T cell, or natural killer cell lineage (CL:0000542).

label.value: positive regulation of lymphocyte apoptotic process

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of lymphocyte death by apoptotic process.

definition.value: Note that a lymphocyte is a cell of the B cell, T cell, or natural killer cell lineage (CL:0000542).

value.value: Any apoptotic process in a T cell, a type of lymphocyte whose defining characteristic is the expression of a T cell receptor complex.

label.value: regulation of T cell apoptotic process

value.value: Any process that modulates the occurrence or rate of T cell death by apoptotic process.

label.value: negative regulation of T cell apoptotic process

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of T cell death by apoptotic process.

label.value: positive regulation of T cell apoptotic process

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of T cell death by apoptotic process.

label.value: regulation of activation-induced cell death of T cells

value.value: Any process that modulates the occurrence or rate of activation-induced cell death of T cells.

label.value: negative regulation of activation-induced cell death of T cells

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of activation-induced cell death of T cells.

label.value: positive regulation of activation-induced cell death of T cells

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of activation-induced cell death of T cells.

label.value: activated T cell autonomous cell death

value.value: A T cell apoptotic process that occurs towards the end of the expansion phase following the initial activation of mature T cells by antigen via the accumulation of pro-apoptotic gene products and decrease in anti-apoptotic gene products.

label.value: regulation of activated T cell autonomous cell death

value.value: Any process that modulates the occurrence or rate of activated T cell autonomous cell death.

label.value: negative regulation of activated T cell autonomous cell death

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of activated T cell autonomous cell death.
